00:00:14.440 --> 00:00:16.690
PRAKASH HARIRAMANI: So as
you saw in the last session,

00:00:16.690 --> 00:00:19.210
for those of you who were here
for Android Pay Everywhere,

00:00:19.210 --> 00:00:21.720
Android Pay is not
just about payments.

00:00:21.720 --> 00:00:25.570
It's about enhancing the
entire in-store experience.

00:00:25.570 --> 00:00:27.560
Sending your card,
your payment card

00:00:27.560 --> 00:00:30.370
to the merchant or retailer
was just the first step,

00:00:30.370 --> 00:00:32.100
but there's more
to it than that.

00:00:32.100 --> 00:00:34.770
When I go and make a
purchase in-store typically,

00:00:34.770 --> 00:00:36.630
in addition to my
payment card, I also

00:00:36.630 --> 00:00:40.620
enter a loyalty card, a
gift card, and/or an offer.

00:00:40.620 --> 00:00:43.250
And that's what we're
going to talk about today.

00:00:43.250 --> 00:00:46.240
So we're going to talk about
three key stakeholders today--

00:00:46.240 --> 00:00:51.310
users, merchants,
and issuers or banks.

00:00:51.310 --> 00:00:53.170
Now for users we're
going to show you

00:00:53.170 --> 00:00:56.320
how users can go beyond
payments, how easy it's

00:00:56.320 --> 00:00:58.710
going to be for them
to sign up for loyalty,

00:00:58.710 --> 00:01:00.720
and most importantly,
use it in the middle

00:01:00.720 --> 00:01:03.516
of an in-store experience
when they need it most.

00:01:03.516 --> 00:01:05.099
For merchants, we're
going to show you

00:01:05.099 --> 00:01:07.820
how they can engage with
their customers, how they can

00:01:07.820 --> 00:01:10.030
contextually send
them reminders,

00:01:10.030 --> 00:01:11.930
and most importantly,
Max is going

00:01:11.930 --> 00:01:14.950
to show you how easy it is
for merchants or developers

00:01:14.950 --> 00:01:17.410
to add the functionality
to their apps.

00:01:17.410 --> 00:01:20.010
And then finally we're going
to talk about issuers or banks.

00:01:20.010 --> 00:01:23.440
We're going to show how easy it
is for banks to bring Android

00:01:23.440 --> 00:01:25.630
Pay functionality to
their apps so they

00:01:25.630 --> 00:01:30.060
can connect with their card
holders through their channels.

00:01:30.060 --> 00:01:31.890
So let's first start
with the pain points--

00:01:31.890 --> 00:01:34.000
what are we trying
to solve here?

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:38.250
So the average US household
has about 22-ish loyalty cards,

00:01:38.250 --> 00:01:40.200
but less than 45% are active.

00:01:40.200 --> 00:01:41.870
Only about 10 are active.

00:01:41.870 --> 00:01:43.500
That's pretty bad, right?

00:01:43.500 --> 00:01:46.829
It's bad for users because
you spend all this time

00:01:46.829 --> 00:01:48.120
signing up for that membership.

00:01:48.120 --> 00:01:51.586
You fill out this long form, and
then you're standing in store

00:01:51.586 --> 00:01:53.210
and you don't have
it when you need it.

00:01:53.210 --> 00:01:54.050
You want to save money.

00:01:54.050 --> 00:01:55.020
You want to get points.

00:01:55.020 --> 00:01:56.820
And it's not there with you.

00:01:56.820 --> 00:01:58.330
It's also bad for merchants.

00:01:58.330 --> 00:01:59.930
They're spending
millions and putting

00:01:59.930 --> 00:02:04.890
in a lot of effort trying to
engage with their customers.

00:02:04.890 --> 00:02:07.880
Continuing with pain
points, less than 1%

00:02:07.880 --> 00:02:11.370
of all coupons or offers that
are issued today are redeemed.

00:02:11.370 --> 00:02:12.580
That's pretty staggering.

00:02:12.580 --> 00:02:13.880
That's pretty bad too.

00:02:13.880 --> 00:02:14.380
And why?

00:02:14.380 --> 00:02:16.120
So it's bad for
users because they

00:02:16.120 --> 00:02:19.570
are unable to save money, again,
when they're in line, in-store,

00:02:19.570 --> 00:02:23.270
for a purchase because they've
forgotten to cut the coupon,

00:02:23.270 --> 00:02:27.270
clip it, bring it with them
in the store and then eat it.

00:02:27.270 --> 00:02:28.560
And it's bad for merchants.

00:02:28.560 --> 00:02:30.440
Millions of dollars
are spent every year

00:02:30.440 --> 00:02:33.700
by manufacturers and retailers
to bring these offers

00:02:33.700 --> 00:02:36.300
in front of users.

00:02:36.300 --> 00:02:38.700
So first we're going to
talk about users and how

00:02:38.700 --> 00:02:40.320
we address these pain points.

00:02:40.320 --> 00:02:41.860
So fundamentally,
there's two things

00:02:41.860 --> 00:02:45.910
that users are looking for--
saving time and saving money.

00:02:45.910 --> 00:02:48.770
So there's many things
Android Pay does to save time.

00:02:48.770 --> 00:02:51.940
First, during payment, you just
have to unlock your phone, tap,

00:02:51.940 --> 00:02:53.150
and you're done.

00:02:53.150 --> 00:02:54.765
You do not have
to launch any app.

00:02:54.765 --> 00:02:57.140
You don't have to have the
app running in the foreground.

00:02:57.140 --> 00:02:59.800
You just set it up
once, and you tap.

00:02:59.800 --> 00:03:01.990
And the most important
thing is it doesn't just

00:03:01.990 --> 00:03:03.200
send your payment credential.

00:03:03.200 --> 00:03:05.510
So as Pali showed in
the previous demo, when

00:03:05.510 --> 00:03:07.660
he tapped on the
Walgreens terminal,

00:03:07.660 --> 00:03:10.840
it sent his Balance Rewards
loyalty card and his payment

00:03:10.840 --> 00:03:11.506
card.

00:03:11.506 --> 00:03:12.880
And that does save
time because I

00:03:12.880 --> 00:03:15.610
don't have to fumble in my
wallet, find that loyalty card,

00:03:15.610 --> 00:03:19.030
find that offer, and then
present it to the cashier.

00:03:19.030 --> 00:03:21.380
Saving money is the
other thing users desire.

00:03:21.380 --> 00:03:23.530
So the best way to
demonstrate this

